drinking plenty of water. In North America I drink a 77 oz bottle of water at least once a day. I haven't had nearly enough the last few days to drink in Africa, as I'm trying to limit the number of empty water bottles that I throw out each day. And I've got a guava juice now but that's it, the apple juice was delicious though. Also, I'm sore and tired from all that walking, so I'm sure that has something to do with it too.

Tonight, we met Emmanuelle's mom, Madeleine. She's incredibly hospitable. We took two small tours of the city. The first one we spent about an hour sightseeing around Assini, and the second one we drove around the entire city of Lome, seeing the Lome Grand Marche, the beach, the Presidential Palace, and other popular tourist spots, and then we went back to their electric welding workshop, where Knocky and Baster worked on our pitas. It got me thinking about how important it is to pass on the traditions of our ancestors through example, and how important it is for us to take advantage of opportunities to see how different places prosper or how they live. Lome is a city of 2 million people, that exports mainly iron and gold, and it is the wealthiest fortress city on the coast of West Africa.
